{
  "text": "Previous studies have shown that headless insects, lacking both the supra-and 281 subesophageal ganglion, do not engage in spontaneous walking, and upon tactile 282 stimulation walk only briefly. However, when the SEG was left intact, the insects tended 283 to walk spontaneously and often uninhibitedly, without any additional stimulation (e.g. 284 stick insect: [CITATION_1] ; locust: [CITATION_2] ; cockroach: [CITATION_3] . 285",
